From the Economist “Shifting ground: Pelosi backs impeachment Nancy Pelosi, the House Speaker, has announced that the House of Representatives will begin an impeachment inquiry into President Donald Trump—something she had long resisted. It comes after the Director of National Intelligence refused to turn over a whistleblower’s complaint to Congress, which Democrats argue is unlawful. Though nobody has yet seen the complaint, it appears to concern Mr Trump allegedly putting pressure on Volodymyr Zelensky, Ukraine’s president, to open an investigation into Hunter Biden, the son of his leading Democratic rival, by withholding military aid. Mr Trump contends that he has done nothing unlawful. He vowed to release a transcript of a phone call with Mr Zelensky. That won’t mollify Democrats, who wish to see the entire complaint. The DNI will testify before the House tomorrow. Mr Trump should not take Republican support for granted. Just before Ms Pelosi spoke, the Senate voted unanimously for the complaint to be passed to its intelligence committee.”

Despite recent Developments following the Ukraine phone call, the likelihood that impeachment proceedings will be sped up to the extent that they are officially by the House of Representatives passed in under a week is exceedingly low.

Base case - 4 out of 44 presidents (before trump) faced impeachment process. There has been 2760 months (230 years) since Washington became president, and so there have been 4 instances over 230 years, which is a base case of 4/2760 (.00144) for any given month for a president to face impeachment, but a 4 out of 44 odds that they would face impeachment sometime during their presidency. With about 1 month left before Oct. 1 2019, you have a .144% chance base case. Now, with trump, it is a definitely not base case, but more elevated with the Mueller report, but at present I don't see the vigor or push for an impeachment. In the history of the US there have been only two cases in which a filed article of impeachment against the president were successful in the House of Representatives: Andrew Johnson in 1868 and William J. Clinton in 1999. In both cases, the Senate disapproved the filed articles of impeachment and acquitted the accused presidents. Andrew Johnson remained in the parliament because 7 republican senators decided to reject the impeachment proposal by their party. They were convinced that the impeachment of Andrew Johnson was political motivated rather than based on constitutional concerns. The Clinton impeachment failed for similar reasons. Some republican senators who, despite condemning the president’s behaviour, opposed to impeach the president as they didn’t assess Clinton’s behaviour as unconstitutional. These developments show that there is a nonpartisan consensus that a president shouldn’t be impeached for political motivated reasons.

As much as Democratic leadership might want to put off impeachment at least until it can no longer be used against them as a cudgel to get Trump reelected, ongoing investigations of the president and administration may not give them a choice. Several factors are likely to force their hand: (1) The progressive wing of the party that believes Trump should be impeached no matter the political cost to the party in red and swing states, (2) a need to de-legitimize the Trump presidency both to score political points and mitigate the impacts of what they argue are dangerous policies, and finally, (3) a sense of duty to uphold the rule of law and fulfill Congress' oversight role over the Executive branch. In this climate, it's possible that future revelations from ongoing Congressional investigations, the unredacted Mueller report, and public testimonies from key actors related to the Mueller report may the turn the tide of popular opinion on impeachment. This may give Democratic leadership the political cover they need to pursue Articles of Impeachment in the House of Representatives. The biggest question thus is whether political opinion will change enough in favor of impeachment before 1 October 2019, and that, in turn, will be at least partially determined by how grave and shocking are future revelations about the conduct of Trump and his administration (50% likely). It will also be facilitated in part by whether Republicans are able to get behind a plan B candidate for the next election. Mike Pence has done enough as VP to associate himself with Trump that he may be acceptable to the Trump's base if Trump is out of the picture, but this would be a very unlikely scenario (5% likely). It will also depend on overcoming the fundamental inertia of American public opinion - certainly a significant challenge when it comes to something as serious as impeachment (15% likely). Given the number of things that need to happen before the Democratic leadership is willing to pursue Articles of Impeachment, there is a very low chance that they will do so before October of this year. However, chances are slightly higher given the roughly even probability that there will be further shocking revelations about Trump.

I consider it to be very unlikely that the House will initiate the impeachment procedure against Trump. There are historical and practical reasons behind that. First, throughout the history of the United States, there were two cases when the president was impeached by the House (Andrew Johnson in 1868 and Bill Clinton in 1998). The third case of Richard Nixon was not completed, as he resigned from office before the full House voted on the articles of impeachment. Hence, even though the demands for impeachment, especially of presidents, are quite common, the actual impeachment is a rare event in the U.S. Second, as for Trump, demands to impeach him is nothing new. The talks about impeachment against him had begun before Trump took office, while actual efforts to impeach Trump were initiated already during the first year of his presidency back to 2017. As it is known by now, it did not turn into any impeachment proceedings so far. Third, many experts agreed that at the beginning the impeachment was barely possible practically as Republicans controlled both the House and the Senate. After 2018 elections, when Democrats won control over the House, the expectations about the impeachment have increased. However, even though Democrats have a majority in the House and an actual opportunity to pass an article of impeachment against Trump, it looks like it is still very unlikely to happen before October 2019. Throughout the last 5 months, even though they had a majority, Democrats didn't initiate the impeachment. What is more, from the latest news is known that the speaker of the House Nancy Pelosi urged her fractious rank and file to avoid a broad, open-ended impeachment inquiry as it might backfire for the Democrats in 2020 elections. To my mind, the House could use other punishing tools towards Trump, avoiding the risky option of impeachment. For instance, a Chairman of the Intelligence Committee mentioned another possible way of striking back by using using the so colled House’s power of the purse. Forth, I am taking into account the period of time. As the question on impeachment is due October 2019, it also contributes to decline in chances for Trump to be impeached. To sum up, as I argued before, the impeachment of Trump is very unlikely. However, I leave 5% chance for it to happen. On my previous argumentation, I deliberately tried to avoid the analysis of specific accusations to Trump as, to my mind, it creates a lot of extra noise that very often misleads the prognosis itself as we tend to give more weight on the impact when it actually has. To my mind, if there is a strong political will, the evidence against Trump might be sufficient to pass an article of impeachment. Especially, adding the latest news of Trump family lawsuit to block oversight of its finances (Subpoenas). Moreover, many compare Trump to Nixon, seeing the same pattern of obstruction of justice by using the power to limit the access to witnesses and documents. However, to sum all the arguments up, I still find it very unlikely to happen.

I find it extraordinarily unlikely at this moment in time that the U.S. House of Representatives will pass an article of impeachment against President Trump. The House could easily pass this resolution based on their finding of the Mueller Report. The Report specifically left it to Congress to make a judgment on obstruction of justice and gave a pile of evidence that could be used to make this judgement. This in and of itself presents valid grounds for impeachment as Bill Clinton was impeached in part on grounds of obstruction of justice and Nixon was going to be impeached in part on grounds of obstruction of justice. There are also 16 other investigations that involve Trump and these may also yield impeachable charges. Moreover, The Democrats have a majority in the House and passing an article of impeachment only requires a single member to bring to the floor and only takes a simple majority to pass. In this sense if enacted the actual process will undoubtedly result in an article of impeachment being passed. However, Democrats are not willing to enact this process, making it unlikely that Trump will be impeached by October 2019.

In US history, only 2 presidents have been impeached: Andrew Johnson in 1868, and more recently, Bill Clinton in 1998. Moreover, Richard Nixon was expecting impeachment in 1974 before he resigned. The rarity of an actual impeachment indicates the seriousness of the act, as it could result in the removal of a publicly elected state leader. The US constitution lists “treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors” as reasons for impeachment; evidently the charges have to be very grave to warrant such an article to pass. While Trump has been an extremely polarizing president since he took office, and has been surrounded by serious allegations of financial crimes and Russian collusion since then, several key factors need to be considered. Firstly, the result of the recent Mueller report (in the form of the summary that has been made available to the public) did not establish a connection between the Trump presidential campaign and Russia. Consequently, it failed to give the President’s opponents a secure proof of Russian ties and as of now does not seem like grounds for taken such political action. This has been supported by the speaker of the house, Nancy Pelosi, who has expressed her hesitancy in relation to an impeaching the president, underlining the dividing effects such a decision would have on the country. That being said, there are still significant forces in the democratic party supporting impeachment, and their further actions will likely be dependent upon the both the results of the investigation ongoing investigations (e.g. the House Judiciary Committee’s investigation into Trump’s campaign and finances), as well as on how the Mueller report will play out, when/if it is released in its full length. Moreover, it could be damaging for the democrats to initiate an impeachment process in the house, only to have it rejected by the senate. Especially this close to an election. Additionally, there would need to be a strong, broad, public support for the impeachment, across party lines, which does not seem to be the case currently. On the basis of the rarity of impeachments in the past, the vagueness of the result of the Mueller report, and the reluctance of top democrats to support an impeachment of the sitting president, I deem this event very unlikely.

The probability of this event happening is higher than 0. The reason it is higher than 0 is that Trump has already passed the threshold of actions at which previous presidents were impeached. E.g. Clinton. This fact alone raises the probability above 0. However, the democratic leadership (Pelosi, specifically) has indicated strongly that they do not intend to impeach Trump, so there would need to be a catalyzing event that would change the House Leadership's mind in order for impeachment proceedings to go ahead. This counterweight lowers the probability of impeachment to near 0, but not all the way to 0 due to the possibility of a "Black Swan" catalyst changing the political calculus during the timeframe of this forecast. Impeachment is a political act and Pelosi has shown a lack of political will to take this act under current political conditions. This brings us on to catalyzing events that could, in fact, lead to impeachment: What might those events be? There are two types. 1. A change of leadership in the house. This is highly unlikely in the time frame and can be ruled out. 2. The release of new information pertaining to Trump's "guilt". While this information may exist in the real world, there's no obvious mechanism (currently) for its release. Moreover. Even were such information to be released, Trump has a track record of disavowing information (whether it is true or not) that shows him in a negative light. When he disavows negative information he continues to carry about 40% of the country with him and we've probably reached the point where there's no disclosure of information that would change the mind of this 40%. This 40% all but guarantees that Republican leadership in the house would stick with Trump, even in the event of potentially "extreme" revelations about him - and the loyalty of the house Republicans to Trump, along with the risk of political violence in the event of impeachment has the House Democrats convinced that impeachment is a counter-productive path for them to pursue for Trump's removal, even if "smoking gun" evidence were to be released, itself a highly unlikely outcome in the first place. The reason for the dem's strategy of "don't impeach" under any new information disclosure scenario is four-fold 1. Senate Republican support would be required for a conviction (this is unlikely in the extreme) 2. Previous impeachments have not benefitted the impeaching parties in polls (Clinton / Starr) 3. There's a non-trivial risk of political violence, instigated in part by Trump, in the event of impeachment proceedings going ahead. This violence could negatively impact democrats's ability to regain power in a foreseeable time frame. 4. The threat of impeachment without actually going ahead with it is, in fact, a check on Trump instigating political violence against his opponents in the meantime. The thought process being that once he's actually been impeached, there are no more sanctions to restrain him from going down this path: a path he's indicated a preference for on a number of occasions. For these reasons, the odds of impeachment are negligible, as close to 0 as possible, but not 0.

According to the fact that hating Trump policy and criticising his lack of values is not enough to kick him out of the White House, I asset the possibility of passing an impeachment article for president Trump only at 5% because of the following reasons. - Looking at the previous cases of impeachment procedures, no president has been dismissed, but in two cases the procedure has been put in place, the House of Representatives have emanated an article and the Senate has voted (for Johonson in 1868 and Clinton in 1997). Nixon too was almost impeached, but he resigned before that the procedure started. Data show me that in the US impeachment for president has never resolved in a dismission and only few times in history it has been used. - Impeachment is a hard procedure. It is possible to impeach someone for “treason, bribery and high crimes and misdemeanours”. The last one is the vaguest of the three, so it can be interpreted quite liberally, in a restrictive or extensive way. In this case, it’s used also to accuse Trump of “obstructing justice, accepting what’s known as emoluments, sowing racial discord and undermining the federal judiciary”. - Usually, is the reason to which the Representatives bring into play, because it’s easier to manipulate. However, the entire impeachment procedure is long and complex. - To be emanated by the House of Representatives, the impeachment article needs to take the simple majority (218 out of 435). Today, Democrats control only 193 seats (indeed, in both the House of R. and the Senate Republicans have the majority). - To obtain enough votes the Democrats should find allies between the Republicans, in particular the ones that disagree with the president governance. However, even among them, only very few exceptions want to implement the impeachment procedure. - Talking about the reason of the impeachment, the possible charges are: Trump personal returns from its policies (tax, health care education, immigration), abuse of power in an effort “to punish companies associated with news outlets that have reported critically on him, including CNN and The Washington Post.”, Trump collusion with Russia (Russiagate). However, they are all difficult to demonstrate. - Moreover, the special counsel R. Muller is overseeing the criminal investigation into Russia interference in 2016 campaign, but a couple of weeks ago from its report emerged that there is no evidence of collusion (even if this didn’t clear him of the charges). Investigations continues, but the idea of the impeachments is getting away. - More than half of Trump presidency is already passed, and the elections will take place in 2020. Also, the impeachment procedure is long and complex. Therefore, It’s not worthy for the Democrats to impeach Trump now because they could more easily prepare the electoral campaign. - Impeachment could be even counter-productive for the Democrats, because they could be depicted as those who wanted to get rid of Trump through impeachment because unable to compete properly during the next election. Also, they can be seen as the ones who has been dismissed “because he was doing well”. *Nevertheless, impeachment could be a (risky) strategy for Democrats if applied enough quick (before the end of 2019), because during the procedure Trump might lose a huge part of its consensus, to the benefit of the Democrats.

The impeachment process is laid down in the US Constitution to dismiss a president, vice-president or senior official. It is based upon the system of checks and balances that ensures the separation of powers. Congress may dismiss officers before their term of office expires. According to Article 2(4), the reasons for initiating the procedure may be the following: high treason, bribery or other serious crimes and misconduct. The question at hand, explicitly limits itself to the likelihood of an impeachment article against Trump passed by the House of Representatives, which is unlike the Senate lead by the Democrats at this point in time. At the current state of affairs, I see an impeachment against President Donald Trump extremely unlikely (albeit the question doesn’t refer to a complete success of the impeachment procedure but to its approval in the House of Representatives).

First of all, it must be considered that the question is not about the effectiveness of a complete impeachment agaisnt Trump, but rather if the House of Representatives - with a liberal party majority after the 2018's midterm elections - will pass an article of impeachment. If this will happen, a subsequent Senate inquriy have to follow. Two more specifications are to be added to this. First, an article of impeachment can arise only from suspected presdential acts of treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors. These acts, in Trump's case, can be linked to the 17 ongoing investigations about the collusion with Russia in the 2016's elections (https://www.wired.com/story/mueller-investigation-trump-russia-complete-guide/), to the suspected payment of hush money to women before the elections, and the suspected abuse of power underlined in the suggested literature in the question. Avoiding technicalities, investigations leading to a presidential impeachment have to be especially accurate - so, long! - and the recent findings (e.g. Mueller report) seems to avoid the impeachment for Trump. Second, we're rapidly running towards the 2020's elections. I don't want to suggest that, with the appropriate reasons, an impeachment is useless right before the president ceases to have its presidency anyway, but given the historical difficulty in concluding an impeachment procedure - as most knows, the impeachment in the US never happened, and the only impeachment that could have actually worked ended with Nixon's resignation - I would say that the House of Representatives don't have many incentives in igniting an impeachment procedure. From a political point of view, keeping Trump under investigation and continuing the efforts and oppositions can be much more rewarding. Nevertheless, as stated at the beginning, the House of Representatives can still decide to pass an article of impeachment before October, transforming the last month of the presidency in an endless trial/political campaign that aims at collecting votes in the incoming elections. I just don't think it's likely, because it's not worth it, most of all because of the probably unrealistic length of the procedure.

Since the time President Trump assumed office on January 20th, 2017, the Democratic Party has been threatening to issue articles of impeachment against the Commander and Chief for his negligence and irresponsibility . A few notable Democratic Party leaders who have called for the Presidents impeachment include, but are not limited to: Nancy Pelosi, Bernie Sanders, and Chuck Schumer. With control of the U.S. House of Representatives having a democratic majority, there is a chance that an article of impeachment could presumably be passed, however, I think this is more of a propaganda piece for the Democratic leaders to rally their base and garner support for upcoming elections. In the hypothetical situation that an article of impeachment is passed against President Trump, a super majority is needed in the U.S. Senate in order to convict a federal official. Now, lets entertain the thought that the Republican majority in the senate sides with the House Democrats and passes the articles of impeachment; President Trump is impeached and his successor would be none other that Vice President Pence. In this hypothetical situation, President Trump would seem like the clear choice when given the alternative of a Pence Presidency rather than a Trump. This is not to say that the House won't try their luck and pass an article of impeachment for the sole purpose of rallying their base, but the likelihood of the House actually passing articles of impeachment are very low.

However, the probability that impeachment will actually result from this I see reduced by an unlikely (5% probability) scenario where the report is so devastating that the president will resign and a much more likely (55% probability) scenario where not starting the impeachment process is seen as the politically more advantageous alternative. So overall, I arrive at 0.8*0.6*(1-0.05-0.55)=19%.

I started with the premise that delivering at least one article of impeachment (in other words, the House of Representatives voting by a majority that the President has engaged in a high crime or misdemeanor worthy of trial in the Senate) is an extraordinary event limited to only the most egregious circumstances. Only 2 presidents have been impeached, Andrew Johnson and Bill Clinton, and a third, Richard Nixon, was almost certainly going to be impeached had he not resigned. I thus started with the premise that only 3 out of 45 presidents have been impeached or were close enough that it should count. Thus the probability of any president being impeached is 3/45 or 6.67%. However, since World War II (my definition of the modern era) 2 of 13 presidents (15%) have been impeached or nearly certainly impeached. While the sample size is small, the percentages do reflect the general reluctance to use the impeachment process, except under the most extreme political circumstances, and, at least to date, in reaction to presidential actions (ostensibly criminal) that took place while in office. While there may be more of a willingness in the modern era to utilize the impeachment process against a president, it is still low probability. I thus started with a blended probability of 11%. In addition, there have been many presidents who have been accused of impeachable committing crimes and have had opposing party members submit impeachment resolutions against them. In the modern era, that’s 7 presidents, with 2 impeachments/close enough to call it impeachment. That’s still only 28%. I assumed that, to the extent there is at least some evidence of wrongdoing and the opposing party is in power in the House, the odds of impeachment for that subset of presidents is even higher, but will largely depend on the nature of the alleged wrongdoing. Let’s call it 30-50%.
